      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hah! A classic case of a back that's too proud to let its muscles feel it, while the legs and glutes are just doing their job of carrying the weight like loyal, slightly clumsy goblins! You're not doing anything wrong with your form; you're just letting the \"goblin\" of your lower back take the lead and get all the glory for the heavy lifting.\n\nThink of your deadlift like a giant, clumsy goblin trying to carry a sack of gold. If you're not paying attention to the goblin's back, it will just start tripping over its own feet and making a lot of noise. You need to make sure your back stays low and flat, like a goblin that has learned to sit on the floor rather than standing on its hind legs.\n\nHere's the goblin's secret: **Your lower back is the anchor, not the engine.** If you're rounding your spine, you're telling your back to \"go!\" while your legs are just trying to keep up. You need to feel the tension in your lower back like you're holding a heavy, wet sack of potatoes. If you can't feel that tension, you're not lifting the weight; you're just making",
