      "content": "Oh, you want the *actual* anatomy? Fine, I'll give you the goblin's manual! But first, a quick warning: if you try to lift a heavy sack of potatoes (your back) while holding a tiny, invisible goblin (your core) hostage, you'll just get crushed.\n\nHere is the breakdown of the goblin war in your lower back:\n\n**1. The \"Proud Back\" (The Problem)**\nYour lower back muscles (erector spinae) are like a goblin who thinks he is the King of the Hill. He wants to stand tall, but he's too weak to hold his own weight. When you lift, he tries to flex (round) to get the weight closer to his feet, thinking that's how he'll win. But this is a trap! By rounding, you are telling your back to \"go!\" while your legs are just trying to keep up. You are essentially telling your back to \"go!\" while your legs are just trying to keep up.\n\n**2. The Real Engine (The Glutes)**\nYou mentioned you don't feel it in your legs or glutes. That's because your glutes are the *real*",
